var definitions = ['<h2>Weil ich allergisch bin, kann ich keine Nüsse essen.</h2><div><strong>Weil</strong> This is a German subordinating conjunction that means "because". It introduces a reason or cause, connecting a dependent clause to a main clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the dependent clause introduced by "Weil".</div><div><strong>allergisch</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "allergic". It is used here predicatively, meaning it describes the subject "ich".</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to link the subject "ich" with the adjective "allergisch".</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to" in English. It introduces the main clause, indicating ability or possibility.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Repeated, this is again the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>keine</strong> This is the negative indefinite article in German, in the accusative case, which means "no" or "none". It negates the noun that follows it, in this case, "Nüsse".</div><div><strong>Nüsse</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Nuss", which means "nut" in English. In the accusative case, it is the object of the verb "essen", meaning "nuts" is what cannot be eaten due to the allergy.</div><div><strong>essen</strong> This is the infinitive of the German verb that means "to eat". It shows the action that the subject is unable to do because of the allergy.</div>','<h2>Weil ich müde bin, will ich nicht gehen.</h2><div><strong>Weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It introduces a cause-and-effect relationship between two clauses.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>müde</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "tired". It describes the state or condition of the subject (ich).</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject (ich) with the adjective (müde) to describe a state of being.</div><div><strong>will</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want" in English. It expresses the subject’s intention or desire in the main clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Here the pronoun "ich" is used again as the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is an adverb meaning "not" in German. It negates the verb or the action stated in the sentence.</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English. It’s the action that the subject does not wish to do.</div>','<h2>Er wäscht sein Auto, weil es schmutzig ist.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wäscht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "waschen", which means "to wash". Here, it describes the action the subject is doing.</div><div><strong>sein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates that the noun it is referring to, "Auto", belongs to the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neuter noun in German that means "car". It’s the direct object in the sentence, receiving the action of the verb "wäscht".</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It introduces the reason or cause for the action described in the main clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person neuter singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It refers back to "Auto" as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>schmutzig</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "dirty". It describes the state of "Auto" and provides the reason for the subject’s action of washing it.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here, it links the subject of the subordinate clause "es" to its complement "schmutzig".</div>','<h2>Der Regen macht mir nichts aus, weil ich einen Regenschirm habe.</h2><div><strong>Der</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English, used here for the masculine singular noun in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>Regen</strong> This is a German noun meaning "rain". It’s in the nominative case and is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>macht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "machen", which means "to make" or "to do" in English. It’s used here to describe an action affecting the speaker.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in the dative case, meaning "to me" or "for me" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the verb.</div><div><strong>nichts</strong> This word means "nothing" in English, used in the phrase "macht mir nichts aus" to indicate that something doesn’t bother or affect the speaker.</div><div><strong>aus</strong> This preposition combined with "nichts" and "macht" creates the phrase "macht mir nichts aus", which translates to "does not bother me" or "does not affect me".</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "because" in English. It introduces a cause or reason for the preceding statement.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun "I" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the indefinite article "a" or "an" in English, used here for a masculine singular noun in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Regenschirm</strong> This is a German noun meaning "umbrella". It’s in the accusative case and is the direct object of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It indicates possession by the speaker in the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Ich spreche Deutsch, da ich aus Zürich komme.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spreche</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sprechen", which means "to speak" in English. It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This is a German noun meaning "German". It refers to the German language and is the direct object of the verb "spreche", indicating what language is being spoken.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a conjunction in German that translates to "because" or "since" in English. It introduces a cause or reason.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is repeated as the first-person singular pronoun in German. In this part of the sentence, it’s the subject of the subordinate clause introduced by "da".</div><div><strong>aus</strong> This is a preposition which translates to "from" in English. It indicates the origin or place of departure.</div><div><strong>Zürich</strong> This is a proper noun, the name of a city in Switzerland. It’s the object of the preposition "aus", specifying where the speaker comes from.</div><div><strong>komme</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come" in English. It describes the action or state of the subject in the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Die Sonne geht auf, da es Morgen ist.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German for feminine and plural nouns in the nominative case. Here, it’s used to denote "the".</div><div><strong>Sonne</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "sun". It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>geht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" or "to rise" when referring to celestial bodies. It describes the action of the subject.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a separable prefix commonly used with the verb "gehen" to mean "rise" when referring to celestial bodies like the sun or the moon, completing the phrase to mean "the sun rises".</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a conjunction that can mean "because" or "since". It’s used to introduce a reason or a cause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> It’s the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. Here, it’s used as a subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>Morgen</strong> This is a masculine noun meaning "morning". It’s in the nominative case as it’s the subject of the clause "es Morgen ist".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "es" with the complementary noun "Morgen" to state that "it is morning".</div>','<h2>Du schliefst immer dann, wenn ich gekommen bin.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for the second-person singular, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>schliefst</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of the verb "schlafen", which means "to sleep". Here, it indicates that the action of sleeping was carried out by the subject (Du).</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It explains the frequency of the action.</div><div><strong>dann</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "then". It is often used to indicate a point in time in relation to another event.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This word translates to "whenever" or "when" in English. It introduces a conditional or dependent clause, indicating the circumstances under which the action of the main clause (schliefst) takes place.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for the first-person singular, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>gekommen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "kommen", which means "to come". It is used here with the helping verb "bin" to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". In this case, it functions as an auxiliary verb to form the present perfect tense of "kommen" (gekommen bin).</div>','<h2>Sie sind hübsch, wenn Sie lächeln.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German formal second-person singular or plural pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English. Here, it is used as the subject of the sentence and denotes a formal address or can refer to more than one person.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the second-person plural or formal present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>hübsch</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "pretty" or "handsome". It is used here to describe someone’s appearance.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This word translates to "when" in English. It introduces a conditional clause, indicating the circumstance under which the subject is considered pretty or handsome.</div><div><strong>lächeln</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "lächeln", which means "to smile". Here, it’s used within the conditional clause to specify the action that makes the subject appear pretty or handsome.</div>','<h2>Ruf mich an, wenn du nach Hause kommst.</h2><div><strong>Ruf</strong> This is the imperative form of the verb "rufen", which means "to call" in English. It’s used here to command or request someone to make a phone call.</div><div><strong>mich</strong> This is the first-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "me" in English. It’s the object of the imperative, indicating who should be called.</div><div><strong>an</strong> In this context, "an" is a separable prefix that, combined with "ruf", forms the phrasal verb "anrufen", meaning "to call up" or "to phone".</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "when" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause indicating the condition under which the call should be made.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>nach Hause</strong> This phrase translates to "to home" in English. "Nach" is a preposition indicating direction, and "Hause" is a dative form of "Haus", which means "house" or "home".</div><div><strong>kommst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come" in English. It describes the action of the subject in the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Die Kinder haben immer Spaß, wenn sie auf dem Spielplatz sind.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article for plural nouns in the nominative case in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It indicates that the following noun "Kinder" is definite and plural.</div><div><strong>Kinder</strong> This is the plural form of "Kind", which means "child" in English. Therefore, "Kinder" translates to "children".</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. In this sentence, it helps form the present perfect tense, conveying that the children "have" fun.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This means "always" in English. It is an adverb that describes the frequency of the action (having fun).</div><div><strong>Spaß</strong> This noun means "fun" in English. It is the object of the sentence, indicating what the children have.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "when" or "whenever" in English. It introduces a conditional or temporal subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in the nominative case, meaning "they" in English. It refers back to "die Kinder" as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>auf dem</strong> This is a prepositional phrase composed of the preposition "auf" (meaning "on" in English) and the definite article "dem" which is a dative form for masculine or neuter singular nouns, translating as "on the" when combined with the preposition.</div><div><strong>Spielplatz</strong> This noun means "playground" in English. It is a masculine noun in the singular form and is the object of the prepositional phrase "auf dem", denoting location.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense of the verb "sein", which is "to be" in English. It describes a state of being for the children, indicating that they are at the playground.</div>','<h2>Wir gehen immer ins Schwimmbad, wenn es draußen heiß ist.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the German first-person plural pronoun, equivalent to "we" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". It indicates the action being taken by the subject.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is an adverb meaning "always". It indicates the frequency of the action.</div><div><strong>ins</strong> This word is a contraction of "in das" in German, a preposition that combines with the neutral article "das" to indicate direction or movement into a place. Here it means "into the".</div><div><strong>Schwimmbad,</strong> This is a German noun meaning "swimming pool". It is the object of the sentence, the place where the action of going is directed.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This word is a subordinating conjunction meaning "when" or "whenever". It introduces a condition that affects the main clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. In this context, it refers to the implicit subject of the weather.</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This is an adverb meaning "outside". It indicates the location of the condition.</div><div><strong>heiß</strong> This adjective means "hot". It describes the condition of the weather being hot outside.</div><div><strong>ist.</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here it is used to describe the state of being hot of the outside environment.</div>','<h2>Ich glaube, dass der Tiger wütend ist.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>glaube</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "glauben", which means "to believe". It expresses the speaker’s belief or opinion.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This word is a conjunction in German, equivalent to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause, indicating what the speaker believes.</div><div><strong>der</strong> This is the definite article in German, in the masculine singular nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes the noun "Tiger".</div><div><strong>Tiger</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in German, equivalent to "tiger" in English. It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>wütend</strong> This is an adjective in German, equivalent to "angry" in English. It describes the state or feeling of the tiger.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject "der Tiger" to its state of being "wütend".</div>','<h2>Ich hoffe, dass ihr Hunger habt!</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hoffe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "hoffen", which means "to hope". It indicates the speaker’s expression of hope or desire.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This German conjunction means "that". It introduces a subordinate clause and links it to the main clause.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>Hunger</strong> This is a German noun meaning "hunger". In this sentence, it is used in its accusative form as the direct object of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>habt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It’s used here to state that the group being addressed possesses hunger.</div>','<h2>Es ist wichtig, dass du verstehst.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it" and serves as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicate of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wichtig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "important". In the sentence, it functions as a predicate adjective, describing something of importance.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "that". It is used to introduce a subordinate clause, indicating that the understanding of the person addressed is the important thing being referred to.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the German second-person singular personal pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>verstehst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "verstehen", which means "to understand" in English. It is the action that you (the addressed person) are being expected to take.</div>','<h2>Mir wurde gesagt, dass du zu Hause warst.</h2><div><strong>Mir</strong> This is the dative pronoun "me" in English, indicating the indirect object of the sentence, the person to whom something was said.</div><div><strong>wurde</strong> This is the past tense form of "werden" in the passive voice, which means "was" in English. It indicates that something was done or happened to the subject.</div><div><strong>gesagt</strong> This is the past participle of "sagen", which means "to say" or "to tell" in English. In the sentence, it forms part of the passive voice construction "mir wurde gesagt" (it was said to me).</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This word translates to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause conveying the content of what was said.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>zu Hause</strong> This phrase means "at home" in English. It signifies the location where "you" supposedly were.</div><div><strong>warst</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state or condition of "you" being at home in the past.</div>','<h2>Ich weiß, dass du mich belogen hast.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". It indicates that the speaker has knowledge or is aware of something.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that is equivalent to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause, connecting it to the main clause.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>mich</strong> This is the first-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "me" in English. It’s the object of the subordinate clause, indicating the person who was lied to.</div><div><strong>belogen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "belügen", which means "to lie to someone". In this sentence, it is part of the perfect tense construction in the subordinate clause, combined with "hast".</div><div><strong>hast</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". Here, it is used to form the perfect tense in the subordinate clause, indicating a completed action.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Ich habe geschrien, weil ich Angst hatte.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present perfect tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this case, it’s used as the auxiliary verb needed to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>geschrien</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "schreien", which means "to scream" or "to shout". Here it forms the main part of the verb phrase in the present perfect tense, describing the action that was carried out: "I have screamed".</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German meaning "because". It introduces the reason or cause for the action described in the main clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Again, this is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s used a second time in this sentence as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>Angst</strong> This is a noun meaning "fear" or "anxiety" in German. Here, it’s used to specify what the subject was feeling.</div><div><strong>hatte</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this context, it’s used to express that the subject had a certain feeling, fear, in the past.</div>','<h2>Weil ich heute nicht zur Schule gegangen bin.</h2><div><strong>Weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It introduces a reason or cause and is followed by a dependent clause.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>heute</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "today". It indicates the time when the action did not take place.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates a verb or an entire clause.</div><div><strong>zur Schule</strong> This phrase translates to "to school" in English. "Zur" is a contraction of "zu der", which is a preposition "zu" (to) followed by the definite article "der" (the) in the dative case, feminine gender. "Schule" is a feminine noun meaning "school".</div><div><strong>gegangen bin</strong> This is a past-tense construction composed of two parts. "Gegangen" is the participle form of "gehen", which means "to go". "Bin" is the first-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "sein", which means "to be". In German perfect tense, "sein" is used as the auxiliary verb for verbs indicating movement or change of state, such as "gehen". Together, "gegangen bin" translates to "have gone" in English, and in this context, it indicates past action - not going to school.</div>','<h2>Du magst Peperoni, weil sie scharf sind.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>magst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like". It indicates that you like something in the present.</div><div><strong>Peperoni</strong> This is the plural form of "Peperoni" which can refer to hot chili peppers or small sweet peppers in German. It is not to be confused with "pepperoni", the American salami.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It introduces the reason or cause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. Here, it refers back to "Peperoni".</div><div><strong>scharf</strong> This is a German adjective that means "spicy" or "hot" in the context of food. It describes the characteristic of the "Peperoni".</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It connects the subject "Peperoni" with the adjective "scharf" to state that they possess the quality of being spicy.</div>','<h2>Ich nehme Sie fest, weil Sie stehlen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>nehme</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "nehmen", which means "to take". In this context, "nehme ... fest" forms a phrase that means "I arrest" or "I am arresting".</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used twice in this sentence, first as the direct object of "nehme ... fest" ("I arrest you") and then as the subject of "stehlen" ("you steal").</div><div><strong>fest</strong> This word can have several meanings, including "firm", "solid", or "tight". In this context, it is part of the phrase "nehme ... fest" which means "to arrest".</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It introduces a reason or cause.</div><div><strong>stehlen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to steal". Here it’s used with "Sie", and so the phrase "Sie stehlen" means "you steal". The "Sie" here refers to the same formal "you" as earlier in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Sie weint, weil sie sich ihr Knie verletzt hat.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weint,</strong> This comes from the verb "weinen", which means "to cry". It’s in third-person singular present tense, indicating the action that she is currently doing.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German that means "because". It connects the main clause to the subordinate clause that explains the reason for the action.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This pronoun is used again in the subordinate clause and is still referring to "she".</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case. German often uses reflexive pronouns with certain verbs to indicate that the action is being done to oneself. In this clause, it implies that she hurt herself.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the accusative case, meaning "her" in English. It indicates possession of the knee.</div><div><strong>Knie</strong> This is a neuter noun meaning "knee". In the sentence, it is the direct object of the verb, representing the part of the body she has hurt.</div><div><strong>verletzt</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "verletzen", which means "to injure". German uses past participles in combination with auxiliary verbs to form past tenses, such as the perfect tense seen here.</div><div><strong>hat.</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In combination with the past participle "verletzt", it forms the perfect tense to express a completed action in the past, similar to the present perfect in English.</div>','<h2>Ich rufe an, weil ich Hilfe bei meinem Computer brauche.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>rufe an</strong> These words form the first-person singular present tense of the separable verb "anrufen", which means "to call" or "to call up". It implies the action of making a phone call.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This word is a subordinating conjunction in German, equivalent to "because" in English. It introduces a cause or reason.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Again, this is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>Hilfe</strong> This is a German noun meaning "help" or "assistance". In this sentence, it is the object the speaker is seeking.</div><div><strong>bei</strong> This is a German preposition that, in this context, means "with" or "in". It is used here to indicate the area where help is needed.</div><div><strong>meinem Computer</strong> The word "meinem" is the dative form of the possessive pronoun "mein", meaning "my", used here to indicate possession of the noun "Computer", which means "computer". This phrase means "with my computer", indicating that the help needed is related to the speaker’s computer.</div><div><strong>brauche</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense of the verb "brauchen", which means "to need". It describes what the speaker requires.</div>','<h2>Ich habe mich dem Kamin genähert, weil mir kalt war.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it is used to form the perfect tense.</div><div><strong>mich</strong> This is the accusative form of the first-person singular pronoun "ich", used here reflexively to indicate that the subject is performing an action on itself.</div><div><strong>dem Kamin</strong> This is a dative prepositional phrase, with "dem" being the dative masculine singular definite article for "der", and "Kamin" meaning "fireplace". The preposition "zu" (to) is implied here and omitted in the past participle "genähert" that follows.</div><div><strong>genähert</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "nähern", which means "to approach". Here, it is used with the auxiliary verb "habe" to form the perfect tense and it implies the preposition "zu" which is why "dem Kamin" is dative.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinate conjunction meaning "because". It introduces the reason or cause for the action.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the dative form of "ich", meaning "to me". In this context, it indicates the indirect object – the person experiencing the cold.</div><div><strong>kalt</strong> This is an adjective meaning "cold". In this sentence, it’s used to describe the state of feeling cold.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It indicates the state of being cold in the past.</div>','<h2>Sie werden den ganzen Tag lächeln, weil sie glücklich sind.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German third-person plural pronoun equivalent to "they" in English. It is also the formal "you" but in this context, it represents "they" as indicated by the rest of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the auxiliary verb used for the future tense in German. In this sentence, it indicates a future action - "they will" smile.</div><div><strong>den ganzen Tag</strong> This phrase means "the whole day" or "all day" in English. "Den" is the masculine accusative article for "the", "ganzen" is an adjective meaning "whole" or "entire", and "Tag" is the noun "day".</div><div><strong>lächeln</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb that means "to smile" in English. It is placed at the end of the clause due to the sentence structure rules of German when a modal verb like "werden" is present.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction that means "because" in English. It introduces the reason for the action mentioned in the main clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is again the third-person plural pronoun equivalent to "they" in English. Its use here indicates the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>glücklich</strong> This is an adjective meaning "happy" in English. It describes the state or feeling of "sie" (they).</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It serves as the conjugated verb for the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Ich werde nicht fallen, weil ich einen Klettergurt habe.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which means "to become" or used to form the future tense. In this sentence, it’s used to express a future action ("will not fall").</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates the verb of the sentence, indicating that the action will not happen.</div><div><strong>fallen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb meaning "to fall". In this sentence, used with "werde" it forms the future tense.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "because". It introduces a cause or reason.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Repeated, this is the first-person singular pronoun in German, meaning "I". Here it is used again as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative masculine singular indefinite article in German, translated as "a" or "an" in English. It precedes the noun "Klettergurt".</div><div><strong>Klettergurt</strong> This is a compound noun in German, where "Kletter" means "climbing" and "Gurt" means "belt". Together, "Klettergurt" means "climbing harness". It is the direct object of the subordinate clause, explaining what prevents the fall.</div>','<h2>Er hat eine Bandage gebraucht, weil er sich den Fuß verletzt hatte.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular personal pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it is used to form the perfect tense.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the indefinite article in German, in the accusative case, feminine singular, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>Bandage</strong> This is a German noun meaning "bandage". It’s a feminine singular noun in the accusative case as it’s the direct object of the verb "gebraucht".</div><div><strong>gebraucht</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "brauchen", which means "to need". It’s used here to form the perfect tense with the auxiliary verb "hat".</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a German subordinating conjunction meaning "because". It introduces a reason or cause.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is a repetition of the third-person singular personal pronoun, "he" in English, used here to be the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, used here with a reflexive verb "verletzen", which means that the subject and object of the action are the same person.</div><div><strong>den Fuß</strong> This phrase consists of the definite article "den" in the masculine singular accusative form followed by "Fuß", which means "foot". Together, this is the direct object in the subordinate clause, "the foot".</div><div><strong>verletzt</strong> This is the past participle form of the verb "verletzen", which means "to injure".</div><div><strong>hatte</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", used here to form the past perfect (pluperfect) tense in the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Sie wird ihre Haare waschen, weil sie schmutzig sind.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which means "will" in English. It’s used to form the future tense here.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "her" in English. It shows possession, indicating that the hair belongs to "sie" (she).</div><div><strong>Haare</strong> This is the German word for "hair", and it is plural in this context.</div><div><strong>waschen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to wash". In this sentence, it is used with "wird" to form the future tense.</div><div><strong>weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction that introduces a reason or cause. It is equivalent to "because" in English.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is also the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It refers back to "Haare" (hair), which is plural.</div><div><strong>schmutzig</strong> This is the German adjective for "dirty". It describes the state of the hair.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It links the subject (hair) with the adjective (dirty).</div>','<h2>Weil sie keine Mäntel haben, werden sie sich erkälten.</h2><div><strong>Weil</strong> This is a German subordinating conjunction that means "because". It introduces a cause-and-effect relationship and requires the verb to go to the end of the clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>keine</strong> This is the negative article in German, equivalent to "no" or "not any" in English. Used here it negates the noun "Mäntel".</div><div><strong>Mäntel</strong> This is the plural form of "Mantel", a noun in German meaning "coats".</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the present tense plural form of "haben", a verb in German that means "to have". It’s placed at the end of the clause because of the subordinating conjunction "weil".</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the plural form of the auxiliary verb "werden" in German, indicating the future tense or forming the passive voice. In this sentence, it’s utilized to form the future tense.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> Repeated again, it is the third-person plural pronoun used as the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>sich</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, meaning "themselves" in English. It’s used here with the reflexive verb "erkälten".</div><div><strong>erkälten</strong> This is the infinitive form of a reflexive verb "sich erkälten", which means "to catch a cold". Paired with "werden", it indicates a future likelihood of catching a cold.</div>','<h2>Weil wir einundzwanzig Jahre alt sind, dürfen wir Bier trinken.</h2><div><strong>Weil</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German which means "because". It introduces a reason or a cause.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It serves as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>einundzwanzig</strong> This is a compound number in German which means "twenty-one". German combines words to form compound numbers.</div><div><strong>Jahre</strong> This is the plural form of the German word "Jahr", which means "year". In the context of the sentence, it refers to "years" of age.</div><div><strong>alt</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "old". Used here with "Jahre", it describes the age of the subject.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in German. It links the subject to the adjective describing their age.</div><div><strong>dürfen</strong> This is a modal verb in German that means "to be allowed to" or "may". It indicates permission.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> The subject pronoun is repeated here because German requires the subject to be present with the main verb of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Bier</strong> This is a German noun meaning "beer".</div><div><strong>trinken</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to drink" in German. It follows the modal verb to express what action is permitted.</div>','<h2>Da es zu kalt zum Skifahren war, bin ich in den Skiort gegangen.</h2><div><strong>Da</strong> This is a conjunction in German, which can be translated as "since" or "because". It introduces a cause or reason for something that will be mentioned later in the sentence.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It often acts as a placeholder subject in sentences.</div><div><strong>zu kalt</strong> This phrase means "too cold" in English. "Zu" translates as "too", indicating an excessive degree or amount, and "kalt" is an adjective meaning "cold".</div><div><strong>zum Skifahren</strong> This is a phrase that means "for skiing". The word "zum" is a contraction of "zu dem", a preposition and definite article which, in this context, can be translated as "for" or "to". "Skifahren" is the infinitive form of the verb "to ski".</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being of the subject in the past tense.</div><div><strong>bin</strong> This is the first-person singular present perfect tense form of the verb "sein", used here as an auxiliary verb to form the past tense.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the second part of the sentence.</div><div><strong>in den Skiort</strong> This phrase means "to the ski resort". "In" is a preposition that often indicates direction or location, "den" is the masculine singular form of the definite article "the", and "Skiort" is a compound noun meaning "ski resort".</div><div><strong>gegangen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" in English. Used here with "bin", it forms the present perfect tense, indicating a completed action. </div>','<h2>Da ihr zum Lebensmittelladen fahrt, könnt ihr mir eine Tüte Milch mitbringen?</h2><div><strong>Da</strong> This word means "since" or "as" in English, creating a causal link between two parts of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" (plural) in English. It’s the subject of the sentence in this case.</div><div><strong>zum</strong> "Zum" is a contraction of "zu dem", which literally means "to the" in English. "Zu" is a preposition that can mean "to" or "towards", and "dem" is the dative masculine/neuter definite article, translating as "the". Here, it’s used before the noun for "grocery store".</div><div><strong>Lebensmittelladen</strong> This compound noun means "grocery store" or "food store", combining the words "Lebensmittel" (groceries) and "Laden" (store).</div><div><strong>fahrt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive", "to ride" or "to go to". It indicates the action the subject (you all) is taking.</div><div><strong>könnt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the modal verb "können", which corresponds to "can" or "be able to" in English. It indicates ability or possibility.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> (repeated) The subject pronoun is repeated here for emphasis, and as part of the question structure asking the addressees if they can do something.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in the dative case, meaning "to me" or "for me" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the verb "mitbringen".</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the feminine singular indefinite article in German, which translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>Tüte</strong> This noun means "bag" in English. In combination with "Milch", it refers to a bag of milk, which is a common way milk is sold in some countries.</div><div><strong>Milch</strong> This noun means "milk" in English.</div><div><strong>mitbringen</strong> This is a separable verb that combines "mit" (with) and "bringen" (bring), meaning "to bring along" or "to bring with" in English. It’s the main verb in the final part of the question, asking if the subject can bring milk along with them.</div>','<h2>Ihr werdet weinen, wenn Monika ankommt.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It is the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>werdet</strong> This word is the second-person plural future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which means "to become". In this context, it is used to form the future tense, indicating an action that will occur.</div><div><strong>weinen,</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "weinen", which means "to cry" or "to weep". In this sentence, it is the main verb indicating the action that will be performed by the subject in the future.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This word translates to "when" in English. It’s a subordinating conjunction used to introduce a dependent clause, implying a condition or a specific time.</div><div><strong>Monika</strong> This is a proper noun, a first name referring to a female individual. In English, this name remains "Monika".</div><div><strong>ankommt.</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense of the verb "ankommen", which means "to arrive". In this sentence, it shows the action that will trigger the condition of the main clause (the arrival of Monika causes the subjects to cry).</div>','<h2>Wenn es schneit, gehen sie spazieren.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German subordinating conjunction that translates to "if" or "when" in English. It’s used to introduce a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. Here, it’s used as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>schneit</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "schneien", which means "to snow". It describes the action happening when the condition is met.</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go" or "to walk". It’s used here to indicate the action the subjects will take.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. Here, it’s the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>spazieren</strong> This is a separable verb "spazierengehen" in its infinitive form without the prefix "gehen" attached to the front. It means "to go for a walk" or "to stroll" in English. In this sentence, it’s the activity the subjects engage in when it snows.</div>','<h2>Sie lernt besser, wenn sie draußen ist.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It serves as the subject of the sentence and is capitalized as all German nouns and pronouns are at the beginning of sentences.</div><div><strong>lernt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "lernen", which means "to learn". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>besser</strong> This is a comparative adverb in German meaning "better". It modifies the verb "lernt" and indicates that the learning process is improved under certain conditions.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This word translates to "when" or "if" in English. It introduces a conditional clause, expressing the circumstance under which the subject learns better.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> Again, this is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s used here for the second time in the conditional clause, with a lowercase "s" since it is not at the beginning of the sentence.</div><div><strong>draußen</strong> This is an adverb meaning "outside". It describes the location where the subject learns better.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Together with "draußen" it forms the predicate in the conditional clause, informing about the subject’s location.</div>','<h2>Du bist immer fröhlich, wenn du aufwachst.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bist</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "always". It denotes the frequency of the state being described.</div><div><strong>fröhlich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "cheerful" or "happy". Here, it describes the subject’s emotional state.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "when" or "whenever". It introduces a conditional or temporal clause.</div><div><strong>du</strong> Again, this is the second-person singular pronoun in German, meaning "you". It’s also the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>aufwachst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "aufwachen", which means "to wake up". It indicates the action taking place when the subject is cheerful.</div>','<h2>Du wirst hereinkommen, wenn du sauber bist.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wirst</strong> This is the second-person singular future tense form of the verb "werden", which means "will" when used as an auxiliary verb. It indicates future action.</div><div><strong>hereinkommen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the separable prefix verb "hereinkommen", which means "to come in" or "to enter". It’s used here to show the action that "Du" will do in the future.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "if" or "when". It introduces a condition.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is a repetition of the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here to refer to the same subject in the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>sauber</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "clean".</div><div><strong>bist</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It’s used here to link the subject "du" with the condition "sauber" (clean).</div>','<h2>Der Boden wird rutschig, wenn er nass ist.</h2><div><strong>Der</strong> This is the definite article in German for masculine nouns in the nominative case, translated as "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Boden</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "floor" or "ground". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wird</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "werden" in German, which is used to form the future tense, or to express a state of becoming. Here, it is used to indicate that the floor "becomes" something, hence "gets" or "becomes" in English.</div><div><strong>rutschig</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "slippery". It describes the condition of the floor when it becomes wet.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German meaning "when" or "if". It introduces a condition that affects the main clause.</div><div><strong>er</strong> This is the third-person singular personal pronoun in the nominative case, referring back to "Boden" and translated as "it" in English.</div><div><strong>nass</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "wet". It describes the condition of the floor that triggers it to become "rutschig".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the adjective "nass" to the pronoun "er", completing the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Sie bitten um Hilfe, wenn sie nicht verstehen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and can also be used as a polite form for "you" when addressing someone formally in the singular.</div><div><strong>bitten</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "bitten", which means "to ask for" or "to request". In this sentence, it is conjugated to match the third-person plural subject "Sie".</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a preposition in German that, in this context, means "for". It is used with the verb "bitten" to form the phrase "bitten um", which means "to ask for".</div><div><strong>Hilfe</strong> This is the German noun for "help". It is in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "bitten".</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction in German meaning "when" or "if". It introduces a condition or a dependent clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. In this part of the sentence, it refers to the same subject and starts the dependent clause. It’s identical in form to the pronoun at the beginning but serves as the subject of the subordinate clause here.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is an adverb meaning "not" in German. It negates the verb that follows it.</div><div><strong>verstehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to understand" in German. In this clause, it is used without personal conjugation because "wenn" (when/if) indicates the non-finite form of the verb in the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Wir werden Sie rufen, wenn Ihre Bestellung fertig ist.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the future tense auxiliary verb in German, used here to form the future tense. It translates to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence and is capitalized as a form of politeness in the German language.</div><div><strong>rufen,</strong> This is the main verb in its infinitive form meaning "to call". In this sentence, it’s combined with the auxiliary verb "werden" to express the future tense.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a subordinating conjunction meaning "when" or "if". It introduces a dependent clause indicating the condition under which the action of the main clause will take place.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "your" in the formal sense and is the feminine/plural form to agree with "Bestellung". It indicates possession of the order by the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>Bestellung</strong> This is a feminine noun meaning "order" as in a purchase or a request for goods or services.</div><div><strong>fertig</strong> This is an adjective meaning "ready" or "finished". In this context, it describes the state of the "Bestellung" (order).</div><div><strong>ist.</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It serves as the verb for the dependent clause initiated by "wenn".</div>','<h2>Sei leise, wenn Leute dir etwas erzählen.</h2><div><strong>Sei</strong> This is the imperative form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It is used here to give a command or instruction - "Be" quiet or silent.</div><div><strong>leise</strong> This is an adjective meaning "quiet" or "soft". In the imperative form, it acts as an adverb telling how to be—quietly, or to not make noise.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "when" or "if". It introduces a conditional clause.</div><div><strong>Leute</strong> This is a noun meaning "people" or "folks". It is the subject of the subordinate clause introduced by "wenn".</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the dative case of the second-person singular or plural pronoun "du", similar to the English "to you". It indicates to whom the people are telling something.</div><div><strong>etwas</strong> This is a pronoun that means "something". It stands for the unspecified content of what the people are telling.</div><div><strong>erzählen</strong> This is a verb meaning "to tell" or "to narrate". It is used here in its infinitive form as part of the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Alles ist möglich, wenn du es wirklich willst.</h2><div><strong>Alles</strong> This is the German word for "everything". It is a pronoun used here to refer to all things or possibilities.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is a third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "alles" to the predicate "möglich".</div><div><strong>möglich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "possible". It describes the state or quality of everything being discussed in the sentence.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a condition that must be met for the statement to be true.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. Here, "es" is the direct object of the verb "willst", referring back to the predicate "möglich".</div><div><strong>wirklich</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "really" or "truly". It modifies the verb "willst" and emphasizes the sincerity or intensity of the desire.</div><div><strong>willst</strong> This is a second-person singular present tense conjugation of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want". It expresses the desire or will of the subject "du".</div>','<h2>Wenn du älter wirst, wirst du ein Auto fahren.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a conjunction in German, meaning "if" or "when". In this context, it is used to introduce a condition or a future time.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence here.</div><div><strong>älter</strong> This is the comparative form of the adjective "alt", meaning "old". In this case, "älter" means "older".</div><div><strong>wirst</strong> This is the second-person singular future tense form of the verb "werden" in German. Here, it’s used as the auxiliary verb to form the future tense, translating to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>du</strong> Again, this is the second-person singular pronoun "you", repeated as part of the future tense construction.</div><div><strong>ein Auto</strong> This is a noun phrase, where "ein" is the indefinite article "a", and "Auto" means "car".</div><div><strong>fahren</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "fahren", meaning "to drive". Here, it’s the main verb in the sentence that’s used in the future tense construction along with the verb "wirst".</div>','<h2>Seid vorsichtig, wenn ihr nachts die Straße nehmt.</h2><div><strong>Seid</strong> This is the imperative form of "sein" for the second-person plural in German, which means "to be". It’s used here to give a command or make a request to multiple people, equivalent to "be" in English.</div><div><strong>vorsichtig</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "careful". In the imperative form, it is used after the verb to describe how the action should be performed.</div><div><strong>wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "when" or "if". It introduces a conditional clause, which specifies the condition under which the main clause is applicable.</div><div><strong>ihr</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" (plural) in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause introduced by "wenn".</div><div><strong>nachts</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "at night". It modifies the verb "nehmt" to specify the time when the action takes place.</div><div><strong>die Straße</strong> This is a German noun phrase where "die" is the definite article in the accusative case for feminine nouns and "Straße" is the German word for "street". It’s the object of the verb "nehmt".</div><div><strong>nehmt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "nehmen", which means "to take". In this context, it means to use or go out onto the street.</div>','<h2>Wir wissen, dass der Mond kein Planet ist.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.<br/></div><div><strong>wissen</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". Here, it indicates that the subject has knowledge or awareness of something.<br/></div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German, equivalent to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause, defining what is known by the subject.<br/></div><div><strong>der Mond</strong> This phrase means "the Moon" in English. "Der" is a masculine definite article, and "Mond" is the German word for "Moon". "Der Mond" is the subject of the subordinate clause.<br/></div><div><strong>kein</strong> This is a negation article in German, equivalent to "no" or "not a" in English. It negates the following noun "Planet", asserting that the Moon does not belong to that category.<br/></div><div><strong>Planet</strong> This is the German word for "planet". It is the object of the subordinate clause and is what the Moon is being negated as being.<br/></div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". In this clause, it serves as the linking verb connecting "der Mond" with the negation "kein Planet".<br/></div>','<h2>Ich finde, dass der Film schrecklich war.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>finde</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "finden", which means "to find" or "to think" in English. It expresses the speaker’s opinion or thought.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause, equivalent to "that" in English. It connects the main clause to the subordinate clause expressing what the speaker thinks.</div><div><strong>der Film</strong> This phrase means "the film" or "the movie". "Der" is the masculine definite article, and "Film" is a masculine noun in German.</div><div><strong>schrecklich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "terrible" or "horrible". It describes the speaker’s opinion of the film.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the simple past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It describes the state of being of the film as perceived in the past by the speaker.</div>','<h2>Ich würde niemals zugeben, dass ich falsch lag.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden" in German, used here to express "would". It indicates a conditional mood, often used in hypothetical or non-real situations.</div><div><strong>niemals</strong> This is an adverb meaning "never". It’s used to indicate that something will not happen at any time.</div><div><strong>zugeben,</strong> This is the verb "zugeben" in its infinitive form, meaning "to admit" or "to confess". The comma indicates the start of a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "that". It introduces a subordinate clause, indicating the statement that would not be admitted.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is repeated as it is the subject of the subordinate clause. Again, it means "I".</div><div><strong>falsch</strong> This is an adjective meaning "wrong" or "incorrect".</div><div><strong>lag</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense of the verb "liegen", which here is used metaphorically to mean "was incorrect" or "was mistaken".</div>','<h2>Ich denke, dass dieser Film am lustigsten ist.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>denke</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "denken", which means "to think". It indicates what the subject is doing, in this case, thinking.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause. It is equivalent to "that" in English. It connects the main clause "Ich denke" with the subordinate clause "dieser Film am lustigsten ist".</div><div><strong>dieser</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in German, meaning "this". It’s in the masculine nominative singular form, referring to the masculine noun "Film".</div><div><strong>Film</strong> This is a masculine noun in German, meaning "film" or "movie". It’s the object being discussed in the sentence.</div><div><strong>am lustigsten</strong> This phrase is the superlative form of "lustig" which means "funny" in English. "Am lustigsten" is equivalent to "the funniest" and indicates the movie is funnier than all others being considered.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". Here, it’s used to link the subject "Film" with the predicate "am lustigsten", completing the subordinate clause.</div>','<h2>Dies ist das erste Mal, dass sie Golf spielen.</h2><div><strong>Dies</strong> This is the German demonstrative pronoun for "this". It refers to a specific thing close at hand or a situation that is about to be mentioned.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject with the following phrase that describes a state or condition.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the neutral definite article in German, meaning "the". Here it is used to introduce the noun phrase "das erste Mal".</div><div><strong>erste</strong> This is the German ordinal number "first". When used as an adjective, it precedes the noun to indicate the order in a sequence.</div><div><strong>Mal</strong> In this context, "Mal" is a German noun meaning "time" in the sense of an instance or occasion.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This word is a subordinating conjunction in German, which means "that". It introduces a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This can be either the pronoun "she" in the nominative case, or "they", or the formal "you" in the third person. Given the context, here it likely means "they" or the formal "you".</div><div><strong>Golf</strong> This is a noun, identical to the English "golf", referring to the sport of golf.</div><div><strong>spielen</strong> This is the plural form of the infinitive verb "spielen", which means "to play" in English. In this sentence, it refers to the act of playing golf.</div>','<h2>Er hatte angenommen, dass niemand kommen würde.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hatte angenommen,</strong> This is a past perfect form of the verb "annehmen", which means "to assume" or "to suppose". Here, "hatte" (had) is the auxiliary verb, and "angenommen" is the past participle of "annehmen". Combined, they form the past perfect tense, indicating an action completed in the past.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German, meaning "that". It is used here to introduce a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>niemand</strong> This translates to "nobody" or "no one" in English, and acts as the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>kommen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to come" in German.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the subjunctive form of the auxiliary verb "werden", conveying the sense of "would" as in English. It is used here to indicate an unreal or hypothetical situation in the past.</div>','<h2>Ich glaube, dass wir gut zusammenarbeiten werden.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence, indicating the person who believes something.</div><div><strong>glaube</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "glauben", which means "to believe". Here, it indicates the speaker’s belief or opinion.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This word is a conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause. It is equivalent to "that" in English. It introduces what the speaker believes.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause, indicating the group including the speaker.</div><div><strong>gut</strong> This is an adjective meaning "good" in English. Here, it modifies "zusammenarbeiten", describing the manner of the collaboration.</div><div><strong>zusammenarbeiten</strong> This is an infinitive verb that means "to cooperate" or "to collaborate". It describes the action that the speaker and the group are expected to perform well.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "werden", which means "will" when used as a helper verb to indicate the future tense. It is used here to express a future action that is believed to happen, i.e., the good collaboration.</div>','<h2>Sind Sie sicher, dass es die richtige Antwort ist?</h2><div><strong>Sind</strong> This is the second-person plural form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. In the formal address, it is also used for the second-person singular, equivalent to "are" in English when addressing someone respectfully.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German, used for both singular and plural forms when addressing someone in a formal context. It is capitalized to denote formality.</div><div><strong>sicher</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "sure" or "certain". In this question, it is asking for confirmation.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "that". It introduces a subordinate clause explaining what the speaker is asking to be sure about.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the neuter, nominative, singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the feminine nominative singular article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here because the word "Antwort", which it precedes, is feminine.</div><div><strong>richtige</strong> This is the nominative singular form of the adjective "richtig" in German, which means "right" or "correct". It agrees with the feminine noun "Antwort".</div><div><strong>Antwort</strong> This is a feminine noun in German that means "answer". It is the subject complement of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", meaning "to be". In the subordinate clause, it acts as the linking verb connecting the subject "es" and the complement "die richtige Antwort".</div>','<h2>Ich weiß, dass du mein Geld immer stahlst.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". It indicates that the speaker is aware of the information that follows.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that translates to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>mein</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates that the money being referred to belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Geld</strong> This is a noun meaning "money" in English. It’s the direct object of the verb "stahlst", indicating what was stolen.</div><div><strong>immer</strong> This is an adverb meaning "always" in English, indicating the frequency with which the action occurred.</div><div><strong>stahlst</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of the verb "stehlen", which means "to steal". It indicates that the action of stealing was done by "du" (you) in the past and was habitual.</div>','<h2>Sie träumte, dass sie unter Wasser atmen könnte.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It is the subject of the main clause.</div><div><strong>träumte</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "träumen", which means "to dream". Here, it describes the action she performed.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that translates to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This pronoun appears again and also means "she". It is the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>unter Wasser</strong> This phrase means "underwater" in English. It describes the location or condition in which she could breathe.</div><div><strong>atmen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to breathe" in German.</div><div><strong>könnte</strong> This is the subjunctive or conditional form of the verb "können", which means "to be able to" or "can". It suggests a hypothetical ability or condition.</div>','<h2>Versuchen wir zu verstehen, dass wir keine Wahl haben.</h2><div><strong>Versuchen</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "versuchen", which means "to try". It’s used here at the beginning of the imperative, which is a suggestion: "Let’s try".</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>zu verstehen</strong> This is an infinitive phrase that follows "versuchen", which is often combined with "zu" in German to mean "to try to" do something. "Verstehen" means "to understand".</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction that translates to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> Repeated again within the subordinate clause, it is the first-person plural pronoun, meaning "we".</div><div><strong>keine</strong> This translates to "no" or "none" in English and negates the noun that follows. In this case, it is used with the word "Wahl" to mean "no choice".</div><div><strong>Wahl</strong> This is a feminine noun meaning "choice" or "option". The phrase "keine Wahl haben" translates to "to have no choice".</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". Here, it’s used as part of the phrase "keine Wahl haben".</div>','<h2>Wir wissen, dass einige von euch unseren Plan nicht mögen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wissen</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know". It indicates that the subject has knowledge or is aware of something.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This word translates to "that" in English. It’s a conjunction used to introduce a subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>einige</strong> This translates to "some" in English and is used here to refer to an unspecified amount of people or things within a larger group.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition in German that can be translated to "from" or "of" in English. Here, it’s used in conjunction with "euch" to express "of you" or "among you".</div><div><strong>euch</strong> This is the second-person plural pronoun in the dative case in German, equivalent to "you all" or "you guys" in English. It’s used here to refer to the indirect object of the verb, indicating the people addressed by the speaker.</div><div><strong>unseren</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "our" in the masculine/neutral plural form in the accusative case. It indicates ownership of the "Plan" by the speaking party.</div><div><strong>Plan</strong> This translates to "plan" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence, being the thing that is not liked by the group referenced.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "not". It negates the verb "mögen" to express dislike.</div><div><strong>mögen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to be fond of". Here, it’s negated by "nicht" to indicate that the group does not like the plan.</div>','<h2>Sie demonstrierten, dass ihre Theorie richtig war.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "they". It is the subject of the sentence, referring to a group of people.</div><div><strong>demonstrierten</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "demonstrieren", which means "to demonstrate" in English. They showed or proved something, presumably "ihre Theorie".</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German, which translates to "that" in English. It introduces a subordinate clause and connects it to the main clause.</div><div><strong>ihre</strong> This is the possessive pronoun "their" in German, which refers to something that belongs to or is associated with the people mentioned as "Sie" (they).</div><div><strong>Theorie</strong> This is a noun meaning "theory" in English. It denotes a concept, principle, or set of ideas proposed by the people referred to as "Sie".</div><div><strong>richtig</strong> This is an adjective meaning "correct" or "right" in German. It describes the "Theorie", suggesting that it is accurate or true.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It indicates the state of "ihre Theorie" as asserted by the demonstration.</div>','<h2>Ich glaube, dass sie ihren Saft mit Absicht vergossen hat.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the German first-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>glaube</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the German verb "glauben", which means "to believe" or "to think". It indicates that the speaker believes something to be true.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause. It translates to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>ihren</strong> This is the feminine third-person singular possessive pronoun in the accusative case in German, meaning "her" in English. It indicates possession of the juice.</div><div><strong>Saft</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "juice" in English. Here it is in the accusative case since it is the direct object of the verb "vergossen".</div><div><strong>mit Absicht</strong> This is a phrase in German which means "on purpose" or "deliberately" in English. It describes the manner in which the action was carried out.</div><div><strong>vergossen</strong> This is the past participle of the German verb "vergießen", which means "to spill". This is part of the perfect tense construction in the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the auxiliary verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It’s used here to form the perfect tense in the subordinate clause.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);